&gt; 
&gt; There&#39;s nothing in NEAT that drives outputs to 0, however the CPPN throws out
&gt; any output that is within [-0.2,0.2].  If it didn&#39;t do this, all substrates
&gt; created by CPPNs would be fully connected.  If you look at
&gt; NEAT_LayeredSubstrate.h, you will see convertOutputToWeight(...), which
&gt; converts the output form the CPPN into a substrate weight magnitude.
&gt; 
&gt; I believe part of the reason why values are set to -3 or 3 is more complex:
&gt; Because there isn&#39;t normalization in the basic HyperNEAT algorithm, there is
&gt; competition between the link weights to have influence, so there&#39;s an arms
&gt; race towards very high (or low) link weights.
&gt; 
&gt; Also note that if you do not have a bias code in your CPPN, the connection
&gt; going from (0,0) to (0,0) will be 0 every time because the network has no
&gt; inputs of value.
&gt; 
&gt; Jason G.
